@NODE "Intro" "Introduction To SamClock"
  @{fg highlight} 
			Introduction To SamClock  
@{fg text}
SamClock v2.0 is an Amiga Clock program with alarm, hourly, half hourly
and quarter hourly chimes. The program also displays the current day and
date. There are larger and smaller versions which can be used. The Larger
version shows the time, day, date and allows setting of the alarm, while the
smaller version just shows the current time in as small a window as possible.

@ENDNODE

@node "Req" "Hardware Requirements"
@{fg highlight}
				Requirements
@{fg text}	
	In order to use SamClock you need:

	<*> An Amiga Computer 

	<*> Workbench Version 2.x or greater

@endnode	

@node "unreg" "Using the Unregistered version of SamClock"
@{fg highlight}
                     Using the Unregistered version
@{fg text}
If you have not sent the registration fee to Samsof and received your
personal registration number from Samsof you can only use the unregistered
version of SamClock. Keyfiles for SamClock v1.0 will not work with version
2.0. Once you have registered version 2.0 and receive your personal
registration number you can then select the `Register Now' option and
provided you give all the information asked for correctly the program will
automatically generate the keyfile.

In the unregistered version the first thing you will see on loading the
program is a window reminding you to register within 30 days and asking if
you wish to register now. If you have not yet received your personal
registration number then select the `Test SamClock' option. SamClock will
then run , but you will not be able to save any program settings (The 
`Snapshot Window' option) and the registration reminder window will pop up
every so often. The interval between this window appearing, being cleared and
re-appearing ranges from 2 seconds to about 30 minutes as the window just
appears randomly.

To register please see the @{" How To Register SamClock " link "Reg" 0} page.

@endnode              

@node "Reg" "How To Register SamClock"
@{fg highlight} 
			How To Register SamClock
@{fg text}

	      To Register SamClock you need to:

	
<*> Choose a password to use for your registered version
	This can be any word you like, in any language (providing
	it uses the English character set i.e. no foreign characters)
	
<*> Write this password on a piece of paper
	
<*> Send the password along with the Registration fee to Samsof at:

			    @{b}
			    Samsof Software
		    	    PO Box 11
			    Beccles
			    Suffolk
			    NR34 9JS
			    England@{ub}


 If you live in the UK, please send Ł5.00 (either Cash or Cheque) to Samsof
 Please make cheques out to "S. Bowers"
 
 If you live in Germany you can send DM 15,- (Cash Only please) to Samsof

 If you live elsewhere in the World then please send Ł5.00 (sterling) or 
 US$12 or DM 15,- in cash to Samsof

<*> Send an E-Mail to: @{b}samsof@thenet.co.uk@{ub} to let Samsof know that
	your registration is on it's way.
	
If I receive the registration fee, but no password, then a randomly selected
password will be allocated to you by Samsof.

If I receive your password but no registration fee, then I'm afraid that your
registration number cannot be issued to you until a registration fee is
obtained by me (and if applicable, cheques have cleared).	
@{}	
 ------------------------------------------------

 As soon as I receive your registration fee and chosen password I will E-Mail
 you your own personal registration number. If you prefer, I can send you
 your number via Snail-Mail.	
 
 After you receive this, run the SamClock program, and choose the 
 'Register Now' option. The program will ask if you have received all the
 information from Samsof, press the Y key and type in your chosen password. 
 BE CAREFUL BECAUSE THE PASSWORD IS cAsE SeNsItIvE!
 Then type in the personal registration number that Samsof supplied you with
 and if all goes well you should get a message saying that your personal
 keyfile has been saved. If not, then try again, being careful to ensure that
 you type everything in correctly.
 
 The newly saved keyfile will now contain your password and personal 
 registration number, so there's no need to type this in manually everytime
 you run SamClock. 

@endnode

@node "keys" "Explanation of SamClock keys"
@{fg highlight}
			The SamClock Keys
@{fg text}

			A = Turn @{" Alarm " link "alarm" 0} On/Off
			B = Alter the Background Colour
			C = Turn Hourly @{" Chimes " link "chimes" 0} On/Off
			D = Alter @{" Dateformat " link "date" 0}
			F = Alter the Foreground Colour
			H = Turn Half-Hourly @{" Chimes " link "chimes" 0} On/Off
		     Q = Turn Quarter-Hourly @{" Chimes " link "chimes" 0} On/Off
		     S = Set @{" Alarm " link "alarm" 0}
		     T = Toggle 12/24  Hour Clock
		     Z = Toggle Large/Small Clock
		     
	     ESCape = Stop Alarm
	        Del = Quit SamClock
	       Help = Show The Keys 
@endnode

@node "alarm" "The Alarm"
@{fg highlight}
				The Alarm
@{fg text}
SamClock has an alarm function. To set the alarm either press the S key or
select the `set alarm' function from the menu, then use the sliders that
appear to set the Hour, Minute and Second that you want the alarm to go off.
When this has been done, make sure that the alarm has been turned on. Do this
by looking for the `AL' symbol which should appear next to the alarm time. If
it is not there then press the A key and it should appear.

The alarm can only be set when using the large clock. If you are using the
small clock then press Z or select `Large Clock' from the menu before
attempting to set the Alarm.

When the Alarm goes off, you can press the ESCape key to stop it. 		

@endnode
			
@node "chimes" "The Chimes"
@{fg highlight}
				The Chimes
@{fg text}
SamClock has the ability to play chimes every quarter of an hour (at 0, 15, 
30 and 45 minutes), or every half an hour (at 0 and 30 minutes) or just every
hour (on the hour) or if you prefer no chimes at all. Different chimes are
played at the 15th and 45th minute of every hour to those played at the 30th
minute. On the hour a different chime again is played which `counts' the
hour of the day. That means that if it is 10 o' Clock then the chime rings
ten times. If the twenty four clock is set then for example at 16:00 
(4:00 pm) the chimes will ring 16 times, but if the 12 hour clock is set, the
chimes will ring four times.

To set the chimes press Q for chimes every quarter-of-an-hour, H for chimes
every half-an-hour or C for chimes every Hour. If you don't want any chimes
at all then press for the currently active chime. For example, if the
half-hourly chimes are currently active then press the H key for no chimes at
all.
 
@endnode			

@node "date" "The Date"
@{fg highlight}
				The Date
@{fg text}
SamClock caters for both US an UK date formats. Our American friends write
the date as mm/dd/yyyy whereas our English friends write it as dd/mm/yyyy.

To alter the dateformat just press the D key on your keyboard.

@endnode

